<span id="freeTextContainer7912082281909512894">I originally wanted to read this book--or rather, one of the books in this omnibus volume, How to Cook a Wolf--back in April, when food shortages were at their height. But the library was still closed then, and I finally had a chance to read this now, when food shortages are likely just around the corner again. Fisher&apos;s wit, good humor, and sparkling prose are cheering. And I&apos;m glad that this current world crisis doesn&apos;t involve Atwood-esque food substitutes like the NuEg (or something like that</span>
  <span id="freeText7912082281909512894" style="display:none">I originally wanted to read this book--or rather, one of the books in this omnibus volume, How to Cook a Wolf--back in April, when food shortages were at their height. But the library was still closed then, and I finally had a chance to read this now, when food shortages are likely just around the corner again. Fisher's wit, good humor, and sparkling prose are cheering. And I'm glad that this current world crisis doesn't involve Atwood-esque food substitutes like the NuEg (or something like that) described in How to Cook a Wolf. I wish I'd had a bit more time to savor this. Reading five books at one go in order to return this on time felt a little too much like over-eating.</span>
